instance VedderElectronicSpeedController : DTDFVocab:ActingComponent [
    base:desc "Vedder ESC driving the motor for longitudinal propulsion, receiving voltage commands from the twin"
]

instance SteeringServoActuator : DTDFVocab:ActingComponent [
    base:desc "Steering servo generating angle commands for lateral vehicle control, controllable via digital‑twin interface"
]

instance virtual_to_physical_interaction : DTDFVocab:VirtualToPhysical [
    base:desc "Control commands originate from the User Interface FE (Control Panel) and are routed through the Controlling FE (ACC) to the Actuation FE. The Actuation FE translates high‑level commands such as desired speed, steering angle or braking request into motor voltage or servo position commands, which are sent to the physical vehicle actuators. Command messages are formatted according to the ROS 2 data model and are passed through the Data Translation FE to ensure correct units and message alignment before reaching the physical actuators. Execution confirmation is provided by feedback streams of actuator status that are fed back into the monitoring pipeline."
]

instance twinning_time_scale : DTDFVocab:TimeScale [
    base:desc "The system requires device clock synchronization with a maximum error of 100 ms, mandated by hardware limitations and safety-critical vehicular standards. This synchronization granularity is applied to all computation‑offloading interactions between physical and digital components."
]

instance dt_constellation : DTDFVocab:Constellation [
    base:desc "The Digital Twin follows the ISO 23247 Reference Architecture: software components are organized into three Functional Entities (FEs) – User Entity, Digital Twin Entity, and Physical Twin Entity – each deployed on separate hardware. Every FE is realized as an individual ROS2 package containing one or more ROS2 nodes that implement the FE's functionality. The mapping of software components to FEs provides a clear orchestration layer, while the Physical Twin Entity hosts resource‑specific functions (e.g., sensors, actuators, point‑cloud clustering) and the Digital Twin Entity handles data management and control. This entity‑based decomposition dictates system‑wide coordination and resource allocation across the distributed hardware."
]

instance dt_technical_connection : DTDFVocab:TechnicalConnection [
    base:desc "The Digital Twin System uses a two‑layer network architecture: intra‑entity communication is realized with ROS 2 (DDS‑based) on the local computational platform, and inter‑entity communication employs a Wi‑Fi network using UDP at the transport layer. The system is designed to satisfy a maximum end‑to‑end latency of 100 ms (Requirement R7). Reliability is supported by ROS 2’s built‑in QoS policies; redundancy is achieved by deploying each functional entity on separate hardware components. Security is confined to the network layer, with Wi‑Fi providing link‑level protection; no additional security protocols are described in the document."
]

instance dt_hosting_deployment : DTDFVocab:Deployment [
    base:desc "Each functional entity of the DTS (Data Monitoring, Actuation, Control, Visualization, etc.) is deployed on dedicated hardware components, allowing a distributed edge deployment of the twin. Persistent vehicle state data are stored on a storage device external to the vehicle (Requirement R3). The deployment model supports on‑premise edge nodes with the possibility of cloud integration for long‑term storage and analytics, and includes scalability by adding further hardware nodes for additional sensor or processing workloads. Availability is addressed by the separation of entities across hardware, which isolates failures and maintains system operation."
]

instance standardization : DTDFVocab:Standardization [
    base:desc "The Digital Twin conforms to the ISO 23247 series (published 2021), specifically leveraging Part 2 (Reference Architecture) which defines an entity‑based architecture composed of Observable Manufacturing Elements, Data Collection and Device Control Entities, Digital Twin Entities, and User Entities, each subdivided into Functional Entities. The implementation may employ OPC Unified Architecture (OPC UA) for data collection, device control, and interoperability, aligning with the information‑exchange principles of Part 4 of ISO 23247."
]
